## Summary

Re-ingesting an already-ingested memory-wiki source destroys the user's notes. `openclaw wiki ingest <path>` (and the gateway `wiki` ingest tool) write each source page with a `## Notes` block delimited by `<!-- openclaw:human:start -->` / `<!-- openclaw:human:end -->` markers that the user is meant to edit. When the same source is ingested again (same title, so same slug and same `sources/<slug>.md` path), the page is regenerated with an empty Notes block and overwritten, silently dropping anything the user wrote inside the human-managed block.

This contradicts the documented contract in `docs/plugins/memory-wiki.md:129`: "Managed content stays inside generated blocks. Human note blocks are preserved."

## Root cause

`extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest.ts` rebuilds the full page body with a hardcoded empty human block and writes it unconditionally, never reading the existing page:

```ts
// before
      "## Notes",
      "<!-- openclaw:human:start -->",
      "<!-- openclaw:human:end -->",
      "",
    ].join("\n"),
  });

  await fs.writeFile(pagePath, markdown, "utf8");
```

The sibling write paths already preserve the human block by reading the existing page first: synthesis (`apply.ts` `buildSynthesisBody` threads `originalBody` through `replaceManagedMarkdownBlock`) and the ChatGPT importer (`chatgpt-import.ts` `preserveExistingPageBlocks` re-injects the existing human block). Ingest was the lone writer that skipped this step.

## Fix

When the page already exists, read it and re-inject its existing human Notes block into the freshly rendered markdown before writing. A small helper lives next to the existing human-block markers in `markdown.ts`:

```ts
// after - markdown.ts
const NOTES_HEADING_MARKER = "\n## Notes";

function findNotesHumanBlock(page: string): { start: number; end: number } | null {
  const headingIndex = page.lastIndexOf(NOTES_HEADING_MARKER);
  const searchFrom = headingIndex === -1 ? 0 : headingIndex;
  const start = page.indexOf(HUMAN_START_MARKER, searchFrom);
  if (start === -1) {
    return null;
  }
  const endMarker = page.lastIndexOf(HUMAN_END_MARKER);
  if (endMarker < start) {
    return null;
  }
  return { start, end: endMarker + HUMAN_END_MARKER.length };
}

export function preserveHumanNotesBlock(rendered: string, existing: string): string {
  const existingBlock = findNotesHumanBlock(existing);
  const renderedBlock = findNotesHumanBlock(rendered);
  if (!existingBlock || !renderedBlock) {
    return rendered;
  }
  return (
    rendered.slice(0, renderedBlock.start) +
    existing.slice(existingBlock.start, existingBlock.end) +
    rendered.slice(renderedBlock.end)
  );
}
```

```ts
// after - ingest.ts
  const existing = created ? "" : await fs.readFile(pagePath, "utf8").catch(() => "");
  await fs.writeFile(
    pagePath,
    existing ? preserveHumanNotesBlock(markdown, existing) : markdown,
    "utf8",
  );
```

The block is located by the first human start marker after the `## Notes` heading and the last end marker. Source text is fenced inside `## Content`, which always precedes `## Notes`, and the generated `## Related` block carries only `openclaw:wiki:related` markers, so this is the real Notes block even when the ingested source content or the user's own note text contains the human marker comments; the whole Notes block is preserved verbatim. New page creation is unchanged (`created` short-circuits the read), and the freshly generated source content is still written; only the human block is carried forward.

## Why this is the right boundary

`ingestMemoryWikiSource` is the single function behind both the `wiki ingest` CLI command (`cli.ts:588`) and the gateway ingest tool, so fixing it covers both entry points. The human-block markers and detection already live in `markdown.ts`, so the preserve helper is colocated with the contract it protects. The two sibling writers (synthesis, ChatGPT import) already preserve the block, so no other surface needs changing; this change brings ingest in line with them.

## Verification

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest-human-notes.test.ts` (three cases pass with the patch). The marker-in-source-content case fails on a whole-page first-match helper, and the marker-in-note case fails on a last-marker helper; both pass once the block is anchored to the `## Notes` heading.
- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs extensions/memory-wiki/src/ingest.test.ts` (existing create-path assertion unchanged) passes.
- `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs` and `oxfmt --check` clean on the three changed files.
- tsgo core typecheck clean.

## Real behavior proof

Behavior addressed: re-ingesting the same memory-wiki source wiped user notes stored in the page's human-managed `## Notes` block; with the patch the notes survive while the regenerated source content is still updated, including when the source content or the note text itself contains the human marker comments.
Real environment tested: drove the real `ingestMemoryWikiSource` runtime function (the exact function behind `wiki ingest` and the gateway ingest tool) against a real on-disk vault on pristine base `88b21fc30b` and on the patched head `b36ef75b31`, with identical inputs. Scenario 1: ingest, add a note, update the source, re-ingest. Scenario 2: same, but the updated source content itself contains the human start/end marker comments. Scenario 3: same, but the user's note text itself contains a pasted human start marker. Everything stayed real (real vault on disk, real render/write path); nothing was stubbed.
Exact steps or command run after this patch: for each scenario, ingest the source, edit the page Notes block to add a note, overwrite the source file, re-ingest the same path, then read the page back from disk.
Evidence after fix:
```
# BEFORE (pristine base 88b21fc30b)
[scenario 1: plain re-ingest]
updated source content present: true
user note present after re-ingest: false
[scenario 2: re-ingest where source content itself contains the human markers]
source content INJECTED FROM SOURCE present: true
Notes block keeps user note: false
Notes block free of source content: true
[scenario 3: re-ingest where the note text itself contains a marker comment]
note kept before pasted marker (EARLY NOTE): false
note kept after pasted marker (LATE NOTE): false

# AFTER (this patch b36ef75b31, identical inputs)
[scenario 1: plain re-ingest]
updated source content present: true
user note present after re-ingest: true
[scenario 2: re-ingest where source content itself contains the human markers]
source content INJECTED FROM SOURCE present: true
Notes block keeps user note: true
Notes block free of source content: true
[scenario 3: re-ingest where the note text itself contains a marker comment]
note kept before pasted marker (EARLY NOTE): true
note kept after pasted marker (LATE NOTE): true
```
Observed result after fix: the re-ingested page keeps the user's note inside the Notes block while still showing the updated source content; on pristine base the same notes are gone. The note survives even when the source content contains the marker comments and when the note text itself contains a pasted start marker (both the content before and after the pasted marker are retained).
What was not tested: no live network or provider request is involved in ingest; full repo build not run.
